    ‚êõ[97;44m Terminal Chronicle ‚êõ[39;49m ‚êõ[90mLow-level output with readable print calls.

    Timeline: ‚êõ[96mteletype‚êõ[90m -> ‚êõ[92mglass terminal‚êõ[90m -> ‚êõ[93mVT100‚êõ[90m -> ‚êõ[95mmodern ANSI consoles

    ‚êõ[96m1968‚êõ[90m  Video terminals began to replace noisy paper with phosphor screens.
          A cursor could move, lines could be rewritten, and suddenly the console
          felt alive.

    ‚êõ[92m1978‚êõ[90m  DEC introduced the ‚êõ[97mVT100‚êõ[90m, a terminal that had a language of escape
          sequences: ‚êõ[33mMove the cursor‚êõ[90m, ‚êõ[35mchange colors‚êõ[90m, ‚êõ[36mredraw only what changed‚êõ[90m.

    ‚êõ[93m1980s‚êõ[90m Bulletin boards, editors, and debuggers discovered that text mode did
          not have to look dull. Progress bars, highlighted menus, and boxed
          dialogs were all just carefully printed characters.

    ‚êõ[95mToday‚êõ[90m The idea is unchanged: emit text, switch styles, keep the code compact,
          and let the terminal shine.
          This demo uses ‚êõ[97mprintLine(‚êõ[93m"text"‚êõ[90m, ‚êõ[96mfg::...‚êõ[90m, ‚êõ[92mbg::...‚êõ[97m)‚êõ[90m to tell a story
          without building a custom renderer first.

    ‚êõ[97;100m Try the other demos next: ‚êõ[39;49m ‚êõ[96mretro-plasma‚êõ[90m, ‚êõ[92mframe-weaver‚êõ[90m, ‚êõ[95mtext-gallery‚êõ[90m.‚êõ[0m
